nd Road Initiative: A Signaling Approach to Trust-Building across Narratives -- tTheme VII Balancing, Hegemony, and Mandalas -- t13 Balancing in Ancient China -- t14 International Order in Ancient India -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aA free open access ebook is available upon publication. Learn more at www.luminosoa.org. The rise of China and India could be the most important political development of the twenty-first century. What will the foreign policies of China and India look like in the future? What should they look like? And what can each country learn from the other? Bridging Two Worlds gathers a coterie of experts in the field, analyzing profound political thinkers from these ancient regions whose theories of interstate relations set the terms for the debates today. This volume is the first work that systematically compares ancient thoughts and theories about international politics between China and India. It is essential reading for anyone interested in the growth of China and India and what it will mean for the rest of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian Studies.2bisacsh1 aAcharya, Amitav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Daniel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Daniel A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBhargava, Rajeev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDatta-Ray, Deep K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/